Organisms\'97plants and animals\'97are the starting point of my research. Through their activities, organisms shape the environment in many different ways. For instance, foraging, interacting with other organisms, or spending time in a given place. At the same time, organisms respond to the characteristics of their environment, changing how they behave. These organism-environment interactions are the backbone upon which most of what we know about the ecology of ecosystems is built. Consequently, investigating and describing them are fundamental steps towards developing a holistic, general understanding of the way ecosystems\'97and our plant\'97work.\
\
My interest in organisms\'92 behaviour led me to investigate what constrains it\'97from animal biochemistry (Rizzuto et al. 2019) to the laws of physics (Rizzuto et al. 2018). From there, I move to study how the characteristics of the environment\'97for instance, food biochemistry\'97influence how organisms use their space (Rizzuto et al. 2021). Finally, I have dabbled in how we as researchers and scientists describe and study the interactions among organisms and environment (Rizzuto et al. 2019, Ellis-Soto, Ferraro et al. 2021, Heckford et al. 2021). \
