\f2\i exchanges of materials
\f1\i0  with their surroundings. In a 
\f2\i trophic interaction
\f1\i0  a consumer\'97e.g., a plant, an animal, a bacteria\'97uses a resource, for instance, nutrients in the soil or another organism, to produce more of itself. 
\f2\i Exchanges of materials
\f1\i0  with the ecosystem\'92s surroundings comprise mobilization and transport of matter, energy, and information in time and space. Trophic interactions within ecosystems and cross-ecosystem exchanges weave a network that spans the globe and supports life everywhere. \
