\f2\i Ecological Theory
\f1\i0 \
\uc0\u10625  Empirical research is how my passion for ecology started but over the years I developed a taste for theory\
\uc0\u10625  theory is useful because it lets you run entire experiments on a piece of paper (or the screen of your computer)\
\uc0\u10625  these abstract experiments are useful to learn about a system, develop ideas, and shape questions and expected answers to then go test in the field with boots on the ground\
\uc0\u10625  I work to expand current theoretical tools in ecology, particularly mathematical models of how ecosystems work\
\uc0\u10625  Animal movement paper, Information paper, J Anim E 2021 paper, Meta-contaminants paper\
\
Empirical, boots-on-the-ground research, like the studies described above, is where my passion for ecology was born. However, between one fieldwork bout and the next, I developed an interest in ecological theory and its multiple facets. Theoretical work in ecology is helpful as working on a piece of paper or a computer\'92s screen provides something that is very had to come by in the field: repeatability and control. I find toy experiments and simple mathematical models extremely useful to learn about a new system, develop research ideas, and shape research questions and hypotheses. One can then take these and go test them in the lab or in the field, come back to the theory to adjust what did not work, and repeat the process all over again. Working both sides of the theoretical-empirical spectrum can be very challenging, but also very rewarding.\
